[[File:Yanai Chausu-yama Kofun 1.jpg|thumb|200px|Morning glory-shaped haniwa lined up at {{ill|Yanai Chausuyama Kofun|ja|柳井茶臼山古墳|12=draft}} ([[:en:Yanai,_Yamaguchi|Yanai]], {{ill|Yamaguchi Prefecture|ja|山口県|12=draft}})]] [[File:布留遺跡出土 埴輪・土器.JPG|thumb|200px|Morning glory-shaped haniwa along with cylindrical haniwa and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|12=draft}}, excavated from {{ill|Furu Ruins|ja|布留遺跡|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tenri University Sankokan Museum|ja|天理大学附属天理参考館|12=draft}})]] [[File:Hodota-kofungun Hachimanzuka-kofun-2.JPG|thumb|200px|Morning glory-shaped and cylindrical haniwa at Hachimanzuka Kofun in the {{ill|Hodota Kofun Cluster|ja|保渡田古墳群|12=draft}} ({{ill|Takasaki|ja|高崎市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|12=draft}})]]
'''Morning Glory-Shaped Haniwa''' (朝顔形埴輪, Asagao-gata Haniwa) are a type of {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}}. They are classified under the broader Category of {{ill|cylindrical haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|12=draft}}. These haniwa are characterized by a shape resembling a stand with a vase on top, with an upper section flaring outwards like the trumpet-shaped bloom of a morning glory flower.
== Overview ==
The haniwa of the Kofun period are thought to trace their origins to the {{ill|specialized stands and jars|ja|特殊器台・特殊壺|lt=Special platforms and jars|12=draft}} used in ritual offerings at {{ill|Yayoi Kofuns|ja|弥生墳丘墓|1=Yayoi mounded tombs|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft}} (2nd century), particularly in the {{ill|Kibi|lt=Kibi region|ja|吉備|en|12=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|12=draft}}).<ref>{{harvnb|Kondo|Harunari|1967|pp=13-35}}</ref> Over time, these specialized stands evolved into cylindrical haniwa, while the jars transformed into jar-shaped haniwa. Morning glory-shaped haniwa are believed to have emerged when the stand and jar were combined into a single unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Asaka City Museum|2007|p=3}}</ref>
Typically measuring 50–110 cm in height, these haniwa share features with cylindrical haniwa, such as bands resembling hoops (3–7 in number) and openwork designs. Morning glory-shaped haniwa first appeared in 4th-century Kofuns and persisted throughout the haniwa tradition, which ended in the 6th century. Early examples show the jar's body partially protruding from the cylindrical base, but over time, the jar's neck and body were omitted, and the flared mouth connected directly to the cylinder.
While notable examples have been excavated from the {{ill|Furu Ruins|ja|布留遺跡|12=draft}} in {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|12=draft}}, similar haniwa are found in most Kofuns with cylindrical haniwa, ranging from {{ill|Yamagata Prefecture|ja|山形県|12=draft}} and {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|12=draft}} in the east to {{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|ja|鹿児島県|12=draft}} in the west. At the {{ill|Ishiyama Kofun|ja|石山古墳|12=draft}} in {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft}}, one morning glory-shaped haniwa was placed for every 4–5 cylindrical haniwa.
