== Overview ==

The haniwa of the Kofun period are thought to trace their origins to the {{ill|specialized stands and jars|ja|特殊器台・特殊壺|1=Special platforms and jars|1=Special platforms and jars|lt=Special platforms and jars|qq=draft}} used in ritual offerings at {{ill|Yayoi Kofuns|ja|弥生墳丘墓|1=Yayoi mounded tombs|qq=draft}} in the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|qq=draft}} (2nd century), particularly in the {{ill|Kibi|lt=Kibi region|ja|吉備|en|qq=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Okayama Prefecture|ja|岡山県|qq=draft}}).<ref>{{harvnb|Kondo|Harunari|1967|pp=13-35}}</ref> Over time, these specialized stands evolved into cylindrical haniwa, while the jars transformed into jar-shaped haniwa. Morning glory-shaped haniwa are believed to have emerged when the stand and jar were combined into a single unit.<ref>{{harvnb|Asaka City Museum|2007|p=3}}</ref>

Typically measuring 50–110 cm in height, these haniwa share features with cylindrical haniwa, such as bands resembling hoops (3–7 in number) and openwork designs. Morning glory-shaped haniwa first appeared in 4th-century Kofuns and persisted throughout the haniwa tradition, which ended in the 6th century. Early examples show the jar's body partially protruding from the cylindrical base, but over time, the jar's neck and body were omitted, and the flared mouth connected directly to the cylinder.

While notable examples have been excavated from the {{ill|Furu Ruins|ja|布留遺跡|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|qq=draft}}, similar haniwa are found in most Kofuns with cylindrical haniwa, ranging from {{ill|Yamagata Prefecture|ja|山形県|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|qq=draft}} in the east to {{ill|Kagoshima Prefecture|ja|鹿児島県|qq=draft}} in the west. At the {{ill|Ishiyama Kofun|ja|石山古墳|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft}}, one morning glory-shaped haniwa was placed for every 4–5 cylindrical haniwa.

